            "Like a car's speedometer"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What device is used to measure the total electrical energy consumed over a period of time?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Energy Meter",
            "kWh meter",
            "Measures cumulative usage"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What specific electrical quantity is measured by a Wattmeter?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Power",
            "The rate at which energy is being used",
            "Instantaneous demand"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "If you are tasked with calculating a customer's monthly bill, why must you use an energy meter rather than a wattmeter?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "A wattmeter only shows the instantaneous rate of power",
        "An energy meter tracks the cumulative total over time",
        "Billing requires the total work done (energy), not just the speed of work (power)",
        "Energy meters act like an odometer to record the whole journey of consumption"
      ],
      "hint": "Consider the difference between a 'rate' and a 'total' amount."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Full System Diagnostic Selection",
    "objective": "Evaluate the learner's ability to select a suite of instruments required for a full circuit analysis involving load, consumption, and supply characteristics.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a real-world scenario, you won't just be checking one value. A professional diagnostic requires you to understand the relationship between the supply, the load, and the consumption over time. You must be able to distinguish between the 'pressure' of the supply, the 'flow' of the current, the 'opposition' of the components, and the 'work' being done—both as a momentary rate and as a cumulative total.",
      "Selecting the wrong tool doesn't just give a bad reading; it can be dangerous or lead to expensive equipment damage. You need to know exactly which instrument handles which quantity before you open your tool bag."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are conducting a performance audit on an industrial motor. To complete your report, you must measure: 1) The potential difference at the terminals, 2) The flow of electrons through the supply cables, 3) The opposition of the motor windings while the power is safely isolated, 4) The instantaneous rate of work the motor is performing, and 5) The total electricity consumed during the test period. Name the five specific instruments required for these measurements in the correct order.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "1. Voltmeter (for potential difference/voltage)",
      "2. Ammeter (for flow/current)",
      "3. Ohmmeter (for opposition/resistance - must be isolated)",
      "4. Wattmeter (for rate of work/power)",
      "5. Energy meter or kWh meter (for total consumption/energy)"
    ],
    "hint": "Match the physical concept (pressure, flow, opposition, rate, total) to the specific meter designed for that job."
  }
}

